acquisitions  the new york times nytimescom no longer supports internet explorer  or earlier please upgrade your browser learn more » sections home search skip to content skip to navigation view mobile version the new york times dealbooknestlé under pressure plans buyback and perhaps acquisitions search subscribe now log in  settings close search httpsnytimsueifls advertisement supported by nestlé under pressure plans buyback and perhaps acquisitions by michael j de la mercedjune   continue reading the main story share this page continue reading the main story photo a nestlé plant in michigan produces bottled water the company emphasized on tuesday that it was prepared to spend to bolster the fastgrowing parts of its business credit gary howe for the new york times london — in revealing his investment position in nestlé on sunday the hedge fund manager daniel s loeb urged the company to consider slimming down as well as buying back its stockon tuesday nestlé said it was indeed prepared to spend billions of dollars on buybacks — but the company also suggested that it might pursue a number of acquisitions in addition to shedding businessesnestlé said it could buy back almost  billion of its shares over the next three years to create value for its shareholders the company added that it would consider making acquisitions in fastgrowing parts of its business portfolio including coffee pet care bottled water and consumer health carethe plan suggests significant change at nestlé the swiss food giant whose products include kit kat bars and stouffer’s frozen pizzas at a time when its onceenviable growth rates have declined as consumer tastes change advertisement continue reading the main story shares of nestlé which surged  percent on monday fell  percent in trading in zurich on tuesday continue reading the main story advertisement continue reading the main story nestlé said that the plans it announced on tuesday had arisen from a regular review of the company’s capital positions — its top managers began the review in january — and that the announcement was not a response to mr loeb’s activist campaign how nestlé makes its money nestlé’s products include candy water dairy and pet food though its candy business has waned especially as fewer americans have displayed an appetite for sweets sales in billions of swiss francsyearoveryear growthpowdered and liquid beverageswatermilk products and ice creamhealth and nutrition productsprepared dishes and cooking aidsconfectionerypetcare sales in billions of swiss francsyearoveryear growthpowdered and liquid beverageswatermilk products and ice creamhealth and nutrition productsprepared dishes and cooking aidsconfectionerypetcare        source  nestlé annual report while the company traditionally presents such proposals in september this time it chose to release the announcement the same day it received regulatory clearance to do soyet nestlé’s new strategic course came out only two days after mr loeb’s hedge fund third point emerged as one of the company’s biggest shareholders and presented suggestions aimed at shaking up what third point described as a significant underperformeramong mr loeb’s suggestions was to trim a portfolio of some  brands to remove dead weighttuesday’s announcement revealed that nestlé had reached some of the same conclusions the company said its board was prepared to spend up to  billion swiss francs on stock buybacks and the conglomerate said it planned to continue to “adjust” its portfolio of operations newsletter sign up continue reading the main story please verify youre not a robot by clicking the box invalid email address please reenter you must select a newsletter to subscribe to sign up you agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for the new york timess products and services thank you for subscribing an error has occurred please try again later you are already subscribed to this email view all new york times newsletters see sample manage email preferences not you privacy policy opt out or contact us anytime nestlé announced this month that it was considering a sale of its american candy business home of gobstoppers and butterfinger bars with the unit in a prolonged sales slumpnestlé however also emphasized that it was prepared to spend and potentially spend a lot to bolster the fastgrowing parts of its business the areas it named as candidates for deal making include those that the company’s chief executive ulf mark schneider identified this year as important growth areassuch deals would be a higher priority than the stock buybacks nestlé said the bulk of its share repurchases would take place in  and  to let the company make takeovers firstthe company said it was open to improving its profit margins another topic broached by third pointbut one of mr loeb’s suggestions — selling off nestlé’s  percent stake in l’oréal a cosmetics company — may not find favor among nestlé’s top managers in february mr schneider described the l’oréal stake as a “strategic asset” and suggested that any change to it be done carefullya spokeswoman for third point declined to comment on nestlé’s announcement correction june   an earlier version of a graphic that accompanied this article misstated the size of nestlé’s sales figures they are in billions of swiss francs not millions continue reading the main story we’re interested in your feedback on this page tell us what you think related coverage how nestlé expanded beyond the kitchen june   shareholders demand more drastic shifts at nestlé june   with crowding in us market activist investors look to europe june   third point a hedge fund sets its activist sights on nestlé june   related coverage how nestlé expanded beyond the kitchen june   shareholders demand more drastic shifts at nestlé june   with crowding in us market activist investors look to europe june   third point a hedge fund sets its activist sights on nestlé june   whats next loading go to home page » site index the new york times third point loebs hedge fund urges amgen to consider a breakup  the new york times sections home search skip to content the new york times dealbook  third point loeb’s hedge fund urges amgen to consider a breakup search subscribe now log in  settings close search supported by search mergers  acquisitions investment banking private equity hedge funds ipoofferings venture capital legalregulatory third point loeb’s hedge fund urges amgen to consider a breakup by michael j de la merced october    pm october    pm photodaniel loeb founder of the hedge fund third pointcredit steve marcusreuters related links documents third point’s investor letter pdf with corporate breakups on wall street’s mind one of the biggest activist hedge fund managers around thinks the maneuver could prove helpful for the drug giant amgen third point the hedge fund run by daniel s loeb suggested on tuesday that the drug maker should consider splitting itself into two businesses a fastergrowing entity whose products require heavy amounts of research spending nicknamed growthco and a slowergrowing company with more mature products that can afford to pay out a hefty dividend known as matureco after the news shares in amgen were up nearly  percent in late afternoon trading on tuesday valuing the company at more than  billion corporate spinoffs have come into vogue in recent years as companies — some under pressure from shareholders eager for higher returns — have slimmed down their operations by shedding noncore assets corporations including ebay dupont and procter  gamble have all announced to varying degrees breakup plans that would leave them running more focused businesses spinoffs are particularly attractive because they are likely to incur far lower taxes than an outright sale of a division might in the case of amgen such an idea isn’t new mr loeb acknowledged that the idea for splitting the drug maker in two was first proposed by geoffrey porges an analyst at sanford c bernstein nevertheless such a move would make sense given that separating the two businesses could make it easier to focus on developing new drugs and attracting executive talent “a separation of amgen into matureco and growthco would likely be very well received by investors” mr loeb wrote in his firm’s latest letter to its own investors “importantly however we believe that a separation would not just be good for shareholders but that it is a more effective way of running each business” by mr loeb’s reckoning a breakup could yield significant results given its current corporate selfhelp plan amgen appears set to improve its stock’s valuation to  a share by the end of  but if the company splits itself in two the hedge fund manager contends the company’s stock could rise to almost  a share — or  percent higher than where the stock closed on monday the hedge fund manager added in his letter that he had run the ideas by amgen’s management team led by its chief executive robert a bradway and found those executives “receptive” to his suggestions in a statement amgen said that it appreciated hearing from investors including third point and that its management team continued to study ways to improve the company’s stock price executives plan to provide an update on their strategic plan on oct  while third point is trying to goad amgen into breaking itself up it has exited from another investment where it urged a corporate split mr loeb disclosed that his hedge fund has sold off its investment in sony more than a year after urging the japanese electronics giant to partially spin off its american entertainment business though sony rejected the suggestion — “regrettably” according to mr loeb — the hedge fund noted that the company made several moves that have helped lift its fortunes among them were costcutting getting out of the personal computer business and improving its television unit’s profitability the hedge fund magnate pointed to what he said was the most important result of his socalled constructivist campaign third point generated a nearly  percent return on its investment before selling out whats next loading previous post market volatility merely a symptom of larger issues next post google invests heavily in magic leap’s effort to blend illusion and reality advertisement microsoft personalized ad preferences to opt out of personalized ads in this browser your browser history must allow firstparty and thirdparty cookies and you must have your browsing experience set to not delete browsing history on exit instructions for enabling cookies and configuring your browsing history may be available in your browsers settings privacy or help documentation sign in hold on… we’re sorry but this didn’t work you can’t turn off personalized ads right now because your browser is currently blocking thirdparty cookies we can help you fix this issue let’s get started depending on what browser you use open options or settings make sure that thirdparty cookies are not blocked anymore to find out how search your browser’s help revisit httpchoicemicrosoftcomoptout and then on the “personalized ads in this browser” tile click off ext about our ads to create a more customized online experience some of the ads you may receive on microsoft websites and apps are tailored to your previous activities searches and site visits youre in control and heres where you can make the advertising choice thats right for you ext where can i learn more about advertising on microsoft websites and apps microsoft partners with oath appnexus and other third party service providers to help present customized content and display advertisements on msn outlookcom and other websites and apps microsoft also delivers search ads to bing and our search syndication partners learn more about microsoft’s privacy practices here you can learn more about interestbased ads from oath and appnexus in their privacy statements oath and appnexus what choices do i have about interestbased advertising on